<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-19T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-19T18:00:00-05:00" n="797" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">617.003/178: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-19T17:00:00-06:00">May 19, 1935—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 9:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>40. Department’s instruction No. 18, May 16, 6 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d797fn2">Not printed.</note> Minister for Foreign Affairs
                            informed me last evening the tariff bill along the lines of tariff now
                            in effect in Salvador is now awaiting President’s signature and will
                            then be sent to Congress for approval.</p>
                        <p>Unless Department directs me to the contrary I propose to see the
                            President on Monday and suggest that enactment of bill into law be
                            deferred pending [negotiation] of trade agreement with us.</p>
                        <p>Please telegraph instructions.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>